Thought_Process: Under the random serial order procedure, when I am called I will be assigned the highest-ranked company on my submitted list that remains available. Because the order is determined by chance and companies have single seats, I cannot influence which earlier applicants take which companies. Therefore the best strategy is to list my true preferences: at the moment I am called I want the remaining company that is as high as possible on my true ranking. Misrepresenting or truncating my list cannot improve the outcome given this random serial dictatorship mechanism, so I submit my true preference order.

Under the sequential assignment (serial order) each seeker when called receives the highest-ranked company still available from their submitted list. There is no benefit to misreporting: listing a less-preferred company above a more-preferred one can only make me worse off when I'm called, and companies' internal priorities do not affect this procedure. Therefore I should submit my true preference order so that when it's my turn I get the best available company according to my true preferences.
